record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent/src/cmd/pr_comment.rs",
  "line": 363,
  "cap": "AUTH_BYPASS",
  "endpoint": "<cli:pr-comment dedup match — find_existing_comment>",
  "rationale": "find_existing_comment treats `b.contains(COMMENT_MARKER)` (pr_comment.rs:363) as the dedup signal, with no author-id check on the CommentEnvelope. COMMENT_MARKER is the literal string `<!-- nyx-agent:pr-comment v1 -->` and is published in the public repo + every prior agent comment. GitHub returns issue comments in chronological order, so any PR commenter who posts a body containing the marker substring (a fork-PR author, a maintainer doing a prank, anyone with comment perms on the issue) shadows the real agent comment: the agent picks up the attacker's comment id and routes the next run through update_comment -> PATCH /repos/.../issues/comments/:id, which GitHub rejects with 403 because the bot does not own the comment. PrCommentError::GitHub bubbles up and the run exits non-zero without ever posting the confirmed-findings list. Net effect: a single attacker comment silences the agent on that PR indefinitely, and (worse) the operator's CI sees a non-zero `pr-comment` step and may interpret that as an unrelated infrastructure failure. The CommentEnvelope struct already deserialises `id` but not `user.login` / `user.type` / `performed_via_github_app` — the marker check is the *only* gate. Static pass missed because the contains() match looks defensive, and there is no tainted-flow shape to follow.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "as any user with comment perms on the PR: POST /repos/<o>/<r>/issues/<pr>/comments {\"body\":\"hi <!-- nyx-agent:pr-comment v1 --> sorry\"}; next nyx-agent pr-comment run errors with `update comment returned 403` and the agent's own (later) comment never lands."
}

