  "rationale": "webhook_git makes no attempt to discriminate between event types — it parses *any* HMAC-verified body for a `ref` field and triggers a scan when the branch filter is satisfied. The deserialise at webhook.rs:177 is `serde_json::from_slice` into a struct with a single Option<String> field; non-push events (ping, issues, pull_request, workflow_run) all deserialise successfully and yield ref_ = None. When triggers.webhook_branch is None (the default), the branch-mismatch arm at webhook.rs:184 is skipped entirely, so the handler falls through to ScanTrigger.trigger() on ANY HMAC-valid payload. Concrete consequences: (a) GitHub's automatic `ping` event sent on webhook creation triggers a real scan — the operator wires the webhook, GitHub fires the verification ping, and the daemon launches a full multi-repo scan against `repo=None` (every enabled repo, per cfg.repo defaulting to None at webhook.rs:204). (b) Forgejo/Gitea/Bitbucket events GitHub does not have (issue_comment, fork, watch, release) all trigger scans too — every notification the operator subscribed the webhook to becomes a scan. (c) GitHub redelivery (the 'redeliver' button in the webhook UI, or the auto-retry on 5xx) replays a captured push and triggers a duplicate scan; webhook_git has no replay-protection (no nonce, no delivery-id dedup, no timestamp window check), so the same `(secret, body)` pair is accepted indefinitely. The ScanTrigger backpressure path at state.rs:42 caps the queue depth (HTTP 429), so this is an availability annoyance rather than unbounded RCE, but it interacts badly with the prior DOS row on /api/v1/findings/:id/replay (router.rs:1707): a Confirmed-pending finding from a ping-driven scan can be auto-replayed by a downstream consumer that sees a fresh run_id arrive every webhook event. Static pass missed because the bug is what the handler *does not* check (`X-GitHub-Event`, delivery id, `zen` field, push-only filtering) rather than a tainted-flow sink.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "GitHub UI → Webhooks → 'Redeliver' on a stored push event; observe `triggered=true` + a fresh run_id every redelivery. Or: create webhook, observe GitHub send `X-GitHub-Event: ping` with body `{\"zen\":\"...\",\"hook_id\":N}` (no `ref` field) — daemon triggers a scan when webhook_branch is unset. Fix: gate on either `header.get(\"X-GitHub-Event\") == Some(\"push\")` OR a present `ref_` field; track delivery ids in a bounded in-memory LRU keyed by `X-GitHub-Delivery` to drop replays."
}

