  "rationale": "promote_candidate_to_finding mints the destination findings.id via nyx_agent_core::store::finding_id_hash(repo, path, line, cap, rule) (router.rs:1278) and then calls s.store.findings().upsert(&rec) (router.rs:1319). finding_id_hash truncates blake3 to 8 bytes / 16 hex chars (nyx-agent-core/src/store/finding.rs:79-97), so the id space is 2^64 and — critically — fully determined by five fields the operator never re-types: candidate.repo, candidate.path, candidate.line, candidate.cap, and candidate.rule_hint (rule defaults to format!(\"ai-exploration:{}\", cand.cap) only when rule_hint is None, otherwise the AI-supplied string flows verbatim). Static-pass findings are minted with the SAME hash function in the ingestion path, so if the AI candidate emits a tuple whose hash collides with an existing static / Curated finding, the upsert silently OVERWRITES that row: severity becomes \"High\" (router.rs:1301), status becomes \"Open\" (router.rs:1306 — confirmed/verified state lost), finding_origin becomes \"AiExploration\" (router.rs:1307), attack_provenance becomes \"ManualPromote\" (router.rs:1315), verdict_blob is replaced with the ManualPromote JSON (router.rs:1286-1292 — original verdict_blob discarded). No SELECT-then-INSERT guard, no \"row already exists with different origin\" check. Trust crossing: the AI Exploration worker chooses (repo, path, line, cap, rule_hint) but the operator clicks Promote believing the action is purely additive. Exploit chain is single-step because AI sees the repo's static findings in its prompt context, so it can copy the exact (path, line, cap, rule) of any curated finding it wants to neutralise, file the candidate, and wait for the operator's quarantine sweep. Result: a Confirmed Critical SQL injection silently re-renders as Open High `AiExploration` (looks newer, looks less verified, may be dismissed by triage). The 8-byte truncation also enables grind-style off-tuple collisions in ~2^32 work (birthday on a *target* hash), so even a candidate the operator never expected to touch a specific finding can clobber it. Distinct from the pass-1 AUTH_BYPASS rows (setup wizard), the pass-1 CSRF row (no body required), and the existing quarantine/promote surface notes (those concern UI flow, not row-identity collisions). Static pass missed this because (a) the upsert sink is canonical and (b) the cross-table identity coupling is implicit — the hash function is shared but the bug lives in a *different file* from the function that defines it. Fix options: (1) widen finding_id_hash to the full 32-byte digest, (2) guard the upsert in promote_candidate_to_finding with a pre-check that refuses to overwrite a row whose finding_origin is not \"AiExploration\" / whose status is Confirmed-or-Verified, (3) namespace AI-promoted ids with a separate id column rather than sharing the deterministic id space with the static pass.",
